<font color="#FF0000">THIS TOO SHALL PASS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 26 15:32:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
DocDel et al,<br>
     I share the outrage at the desecration of the cemeteries.  If the groups responsible can be identified and have any bases within 200 miles of me, I intend to raise as much hell as legally possible. Being involved in veterans' and union affairs has given me plenty of practice. Lock &amp; load!<br><br>
     Unfortunately, it's not only the racists who have no sense of or respect for the sacred.  The Philadelphia Vietnam Veterans' Memorial has been defaced 3 out of the past 4 Memorial Day eves with paint, oil and last year with the stuff used to lubricate roller blades. Am head of the United Veterans' Council guard detail that will watch over the Memorial from sundown Sunday night to 7 AM Monday morning to prevent any further trouble. Am coordinating with the police district; though more than a few of our veterans would just love to help a vandal fall down the concrete steps accidentally on purpose.<br><br>
     Doc, I wish I had the words to comfort you about your daughter. My oldest son once had a losing argument with a subway train, but survived minus his foot and lower half of his right leg. Have often wondered how I'd have felt if he died.<br><br>
     I once read that living is the best revenge, and that means more than just surviving. I think of the Vietnamese ex-POW that spent 8 years in a &quot;reeducation&quot; camp, and has one of the most marvelously keen senses of humor of anyone I ever met. Things can beat you down, but they can't of themselves break your spirit without your inner consent, at least so I believe. 29 years ago I was nursing a torn ankle membrane; while stationed at Ft. Holabird in Baltimore. I was in a walking cast that cut down on my mobility quite a bit. The words of a poem came tumbling out one evening that my &quot;heart will rise in song&quot; despite the current situation,<br>
and the close was:<br>
          &quot;that the echoes shall resound<br>
           in my mind's memory;<br>
           when fearful frustration takes root;<br>
           to sever the shackles of my limitations.&quot;
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


